<DOC><DOCNO> AP880404-0012 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-04-88 0101EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Candidates     04-04 0378</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Mexico-Candidates,0388</SECOND><HEAD>Five Candidates Oppose Governing Party Nominee In Mexico</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Mexico-Politics, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a list of the candidates runningagainst the nominee for the governing Institutional RevolutionaryParty, Carlos Salinas de Gortari, in presidential electionsscheduled for July 6:</TEXT><BYLINE>National Democratic Front</BYLINE><BYLINE>Cuauhtemoc Cardenas</BYLINE><TEXT>   A former governor of Michoacan in central Mexico, Cardenas, 53,was a leader of the Democratic Current, a dissident movement in thegoverning party fighting for reforms. After the party refused toconsider him as a candidate, he mounted his own candidacy in thecoalition National Democratic Front.   He is the son of the late President Lazaro Cardenas, whoseexpropriation of foreign oil holdings and defense of workers andpeasants made him one of the country's most popular presidents.</TEXT><HEAD>Mexican Socialist Party</HEAD><HEAD>Heberto Castillo</HEAD><TEXT>   The party was formed in 1987 with the merger of several leftistparties, among them one that includes the Communist Party.Castillo, a National University professor and leader of the 1968student movement, was jailed for 2{ years for his activities.Castillo, 59, was chosen as the party's presidential candidate whenit held the country's first presidential primary.</TEXT><HEAD>National Action Party</HEAD><HEAD>Manuel Clouthier</HEAD><TEXT>   The 53-year-old candidate, a well-to-do business leader andrancher from the northwestern state of Sinaloa, supports privateenterprise, more government cutbacks, greater foreign investmentand allowing peasants to own land they currently can use and passon to their children, but not sell.   National Action, known as PAN, is the largest opposition partyand for years was the only significant opposition.</TEXT><HEAD>Revolutionary Workers Party</HEAD><HEAD>Rosario Ibarra de Piedra</HEAD><TEXT>   Ibarra de Piedra is a candidate for a second time of the party,the most radical opposition group. But the 61-year-old candidate isnot a party member. She became politically active and formed anorganization to defend political prisoners after her sondisappeared following his arrest in 1975.   The party refused to agree to a primary of all leftist partiesto choose a single candidate.</TEXT><HEAD>Mexican Democratic Party</HEAD><HEAD>Gumersindo Magana Negrete</HEAD><TEXT>   The party describes itself as inspired by a social Christianphilosophy that supports neither communism nor capitalism ``withouta social dimension.''   Magana, a 48-year-old lawyer, was long active in theconservative Catholic Sinarquista movement, a predecessor of theMexican Democratic Party.</TEXT></DOC>